# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: map-projections-viz
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Modern cartography constitutes many theoretical and practical foundations of geographic information systems (GIS) and geographic information science (GISc).
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] What is the earliest known map is a matter of some debate, both because the term "map" is not well-defined and because some artifacts that might be maps might actually be something else.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] A wall painting that might depict the ancient Anatolian city of Çatalhöyük (previously known as Catal Huyuk or Çatal Hüyük) has been dated to the late 7th millennium BCE.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Among the prehistoric alpine rock carvings of Mount Bego (France) and Valcamonica (Italy), dated to the 4th millennium BCE, geometric patterns consisting of dotted rectangles and lines are widely interpreted in archaeological literature as depicting cultivated plots.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Other known maps of the ancient world include the Minoan "House of the Admiral" wall painting from c.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] 1600 BCE, showing a seaside community in an oblique perspective, and an engraved map of the holy Babylonian city of Nippur, from the Kassite period (14th – 12th centuries BCE).
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The oldest surviving world maps are from 9th century BCE Babylonia.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] One shows Babylon on the Euphrates, surrounded by Assyria, Urartu and several cities, all, in turn, surrounded by a "bitter river" (Oceanus).
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Another depicts Babylon as being north of the center of the world.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The ancient Greeks and Romans created maps from the time of Anaximander in the 6th century BCE.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In the 2nd century CE, Ptolemy wrote his treatise on cartography, Geographia.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] This contained Ptolemy's world map – the world then known to Western society (*Ecumene*).
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] As early as the 8th century, Arab scholars were translating the works of the Greek geographers into Arabic.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Roads were essential in the Roman world, motivating the creation of maps, called *itinerarium*, that portrayed the world as experienced via the roads.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The *Tabula Peutingeriana* is the only surviving example.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In ancient China, geographical literature dates to the 5th century BCE.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The oldest extant Chinese maps come from the State of Qin, dated back to the 4th century BCE, during the Warring States period.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In the book *Xin Yi Xiang Fa Yao*, published in 1092 by the Chinese scientist Su Song, a star map on the equidistant cylindrical projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Although this method of charting seems to have existed in China even before this publication and scientist, the greatest significance of the star maps by Su Song is that they represent the oldest existent star maps in printed form.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Early forms of cartography of India included depictions of the pole star and surrounding constellations.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] These charts may have been used for navigation.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The Arab geographer Muhammad al-Idrisi produced his medieval atlas *Tabula Rogeriana (Book of Roger)* in 1154.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Along with the substantial text he had written, he created a world map influenced mostly by the Ptolemaic conception of the world, but with significant influence from multiple Arab geographers.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] It remained the most accurate world map for the next three centuries.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The map was divided into seven climatic zones, with detailed descriptions of each zone.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] As part of this work, a smaller, circular map depicting the south on top and Arabia in the center was made.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Al-Idrisi also made an estimate of the circumference of the world, accurate to within 10%.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In the Age of Discovery, from the 15th century to the 17th century, European cartographers both copied earlier maps (some of which had been passed down for centuries) and drew their own based on explorers' observations and new surveying techniques.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The invention of the magnetic compass, telescope and sextant enabled increasing accuracy.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In 1492, Martin Behaim, a German cartographer and advisor to the king John II of Portugal, made the oldest extant globe of the Earth.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In 1507, Martin Waldseemüller produced a globular world map and a large 12-panel world wall map (*Universalis Cosmographia*) bearing the first use of the name "America." Portuguese cartographer Diogo Ribero was the author of the first known planisphere with a graduated Equator (1527).
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Italian cartographer Battista Agnese produced at least 71 manuscript atlases of sea charts.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Johannes Werner refined and promoted the Werner projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] This was an equal-area, heart-shaped world map projection (generally called a cordiform projection) that was used in the 16th and 17th centuries.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Over time, other iterations of this map type arose; most notable are the sinusoidal projection and the Bonne projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The Werner projection places its standard parallel at the North Pole; a sinusoidal projection places its standard parallel at the equator; and the Bonne projection is intermediate between the two.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In 1569, mapmaker Gerardus Mercator first published a map based on his Mercator projection, which uses equally-spaced parallel vertical lines of longitude and parallel latitude lines spaced farther apart as they get farther away from the equator.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] By this construction, courses of constant bearing are conveniently represented as straight lines for navigation.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The same property limits its value as a general-purpose world map because regions are shown as increasingly larger than they actually are the further from the equator they are.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Mercator is also credited as the first to use the word "atlas" to describe a collection of maps.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In the later years of his life, Mercator resolved to create his Atlas, a book filled with many maps of different regions of the world, as well as a chronological history of the world from the Earth's creation by God until 1568.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] He was unable to complete it to his satisfaction before he died.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Still, some additions were made to the Atlas after his death, and new editions were published after his death.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In 1570, the Brabantian cartographer Abraham Ortelius, strongly encouraged by Gillis Hooftman, created the first true modern atlas, *Theatrum Orbis Terrarum.* In a rare move, Ortelius credited mapmakers who contributed to the atlas, the list of which grew to 183 individuals by 1603.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In the Renaissance, maps were used to impress viewers and establish the owner's reputation as sophisticated, educated, and worldly.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Because of this, towards the end of the Renaissance, maps were displayed with equal importance of painting, sculptures, and other pieces of art.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In the sixteenth century, maps were becoming increasingly available to consumers through the introduction of printmaking, with about 10% of Venetian homes having some sort of map by the late 1500s.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In medieval times, written directions of how to get somewhere were more common than the use of maps.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] With the Renaissance, cartography began to be seen as a metaphor for power.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Political leaders could lay claim to territories through the use of maps, and this was greatly aided by the religious and colonial expansion of Europe.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The Holy Land and other religious places were the most commonly mapped during the Renaissance.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In the late 1400s to the late 1500s, Rome, Florence, and Venice dominated map-making and trade.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] It started in Florence in the mid-to late 1400s.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Map trade quickly shifted to Rome and Venice but then was overtaken by atlas makers in the late 16th century.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Map publishing in Venice was completed with humanities and book publishing in mind, rather than just informational use.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] There were two main printmaking technologies in the Renaissance: woodcut and copper-plate intaglio, referring to the medium used to transfer the image onto paper.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In woodcut, the map image is created as a relief chiseled from medium-grain hardwood.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The areas intended to be printed are inked and pressed against the sheet.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Being raised from the rest of the block, the map lines cause indentations in the paper that can often be felt on the back of the map.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] There are advantages to using relief to make maps.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] For one, a printmaker doesn't need a press because the maps could be developed as rubbings.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Woodblock is durable enough to be used many times before defects appear.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Existing printing presses can be used to create the prints rather than having to create a new one.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] On the other hand, it is hard to achieve fine detail with the relief technique.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Inconsistencies in linework are more apparent in woodcut than in intaglio.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] To improve quality in the late fifteenth century, a style of relief craftsmanship developed using fine chisels to carve the wood, rather than the more commonly used knife.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In intaglio, lines are engraved into workable metals, typically copper but sometimes brass.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The engraver spreads a thin sheet of wax over the metal plate and uses ink to draw the details.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Then, the engraver traces the lines with a stylus to etch them into the plate beneath.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The engraver can also use styli to prick holes along the drawn lines, trace along them with colored chalk, and then engrave the map.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Lines going in the same direction are carved at the same time, and then the plate is turned to carve lines going in a different direction.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] To print from the finished plate, ink is spread over the metal surface and scraped off such that it remains only in the etched channels.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Then the plate is pressed forcibly against the paper so that the ink in the channels is transferred to the paper.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The pressing is so forceful that it leaves a "plate mark" around the border of the map at the edge of the plate, within which the paper is depressed compared to the margins.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Copper and other metals were expensive at the time, so the plate was often reused for new maps or melted down for other purposes.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Whether woodcut or intaglio, the printed map is hung out to dry.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Once dry, it is usually placed in another press to flatten the paper.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Any type of paper that was available at the time could be used to print the map, but thicker paper was more durable.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Both relief and intaglio were used about equally by the end of the fifteenth century.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Lettering in mapmaking is important for denoting information.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Fine lettering is difficult in woodcut, where it often turned out square and blocky, contrary to the stylized, rounded writing style popular in Italy at the time.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] To improve quality, mapmakers developed fine chisels to carve the relief.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Intaglio lettering did not suffer the troubles of a coarse medium and so was able to express the looping cursive that came to be known as cancellaresca.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] There were custom-made reverse punches that were also used in metal engraving alongside freehand lettering.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The first use of color in map-making cannot be narrowed down to one reason.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] There are arguments that color started as a way to indicate information on the map, with aesthetics coming second.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] There are also arguments that color was first used on maps for aesthetics but then evolved into conveying information.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Either way, many maps of the Renaissance left the publisher without being colored, a practice that continued all the way into the 1800s.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] However, most publishers accepted orders from their patrons to have their maps or atlases colored if they wished.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Because all coloring was done by hand, the patron could request simple, cheap color, or more expensive, elaborate color, even going so far as silver or gold gilding.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The simplest coloring was merely outlines, such as of borders and along rivers.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Wash color meant painting regions with inks or watercolors.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Limning meant adding silver and gold leaf to the map to illuminate lettering, heraldic arms, or other decorative elements.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The early modern period saw the convergence of cartographical techniques across Eurasia and the exchange of mercantile mapping techniques via the Indian Ocean.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In the early seventeenth century, the Selden map was created by a Chinese cartographer.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Historians have put its date of creation around 1620, but there is debate in this regard.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] This map's significance draws from historical misconceptions of East Asian cartography, the main one being that East Asians did not do cartography until Europeans arrived.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The map's depiction of trading routes, a compass rose, and scale bar points to the culmination of many map-making techniques incorporated into Chinese mercantile cartography.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In 1689, representatives of the Russian tsar and Qing Dynasty met near the border town of Nerchinsk, which was near the disputed border of the two powers, in eastern Siberia.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The two parties, with the Qing negotiation party bringing Jesuits as intermediaries, managed to work a treaty which placed the Amur River as the border between the Eurasian powers, and opened up trading relations between the two.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] This treaty's significance draws from the interaction between the two sides, and the intermediaries who were drawn from a wide variety of nationalities.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Maps of the Enlightenment period practically universally used copper plate intaglio, having abandoned the fragile, coarse woodcut technology.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Use of map projections evolved, with the double hemisphere being very common and Mercator's prestigious navigational projection gradually making more appearances.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Due to the paucity of information and the immense difficulty of surveying during the period, mapmakers frequently plagiarized material without giving credit to the original cartographer.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] For example, a famous map of North America known as the "Beaver Map" was published in 1715 by Herman Moll.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] This map is a close reproduction of a 1698 work by Nicolas de Fer.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] De Fer, in turn, had copied images that were first printed in books by Louis Hennepin, published in 1697, and François Du Creux, in 1664.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] By the late 18th century, mapmakers often credited the original publisher with something along the lines of, "After [the original cartographer]" in the map's title or cartouche.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In cartography, technology has continually changed in order to meet the demands of new generations of mapmakers and map users.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The first maps were produced manually, with brushes and parchment; so they varied in quality and were limited in distribution.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The advent of magnetic devices, such as the compass and much later, magnetic storage devices, allowed for the creation of far more accurate maps and the ability to store and manipulate them digitally.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Advances in mechanical devices such as the printing press, quadrant, and vernier allowed the mass production of maps and the creation of accurate reproductions from more accurate data.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Hartmann Schedel was one of the first cartographers to use the printing press to make maps more widely available.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Optical technology, such as the telescope, sextant, and other devices that use telescopes, allowed accurate land surveys and allowed mapmakers and navigators to find their latitude by measuring angles to the North Star at night or the Sun at noon.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Advances in photochemical technology, such as the lithographic and photochemical processes, make possible maps with fine details, which do not distort in shape and which resist moisture and wear.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] This also eliminated the need for engraving, which further speeded up map production.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In the 20th century, aerial photography, satellite imagery, and remote sensing provided efficient, precise methods for mapping physical features, such as coastlines, roads, buildings, watersheds, and topography.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The United States Geological Survey has devised multiple new map projections, notably the Space Oblique Mercator for interpreting satellite ground tracks for mapping the surface.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The use of satellites and space telescopes now allows researchers to map other planets and moons in outer space.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The ability to superimpose spatially located variables onto existing maps has created new uses for maps and new industries to explore and exploit these potentials.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] These advances brought more accuracy to geographical and location-based data and widened the range of applications for cartography, for example in the development of satnav devices.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Today most commercial-quality maps are made using software of three main types: CAD, GIS and specialized illustration software.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Spatial information can be stored in a database, from which it can be extracted on demand.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] These tools lead to increasingly dynamic, interactive maps that can be manipulated digitally.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] On the other hand, we can observe a reverse trend.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In contemporary times, there is a resurgence of interest in the most beautiful periods of cartography, with various maps being created using, for example, Renaissance-style aesthetics.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] We encounter imitators or continuators of Renaissance traditions that merge the realms of science and art.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Field-rugged computers, GPS, and laser rangefinders make it possible to create maps directly from measurements made on site.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] There are technical and cultural aspects to producing maps.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In this sense, maps can sometimes be said to be biased.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The study of bias, influence, and agenda in making a map is what comprise a map's deconstruction.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] A central tenet of deconstructionism is that maps have power.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Other assertions are that maps are inherently biased and that we search for metaphor and rhetoric in maps.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] It is claimed that the Europeans promoted an "epistemological" understanding of the map as early as the 17th century.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] An example of this understanding is that "[European reproduction of terrain on maps] reality can be expressed in mathematical terms; that systematic observation and measurement offer the only route to cartographic truth…".
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] A common belief is that science heads in a direction of progress, and thus leads to more accurate representations of maps.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In this belief, European maps must be superior to others, which necessarily employed different map-making skills.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] "There was a 'not cartography' land where lurked an army of inaccurate, heretical, subjective, valuative, and ideologically distorted images.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Depictions of Africa are a common target of deconstructionism.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] According to deconstructionist models, cartography was used for strategic purposes associated with imperialism and as instruments and representations of power during the conquest of Africa.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The depiction of Africa and the low latitudes in general on the Mercator projection has been interpreted as imperialistic and as symbolic of subjugation due to the diminished proportions of those regions compared to higher latitudes where the European powers were concentrated.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Maps furthered imperialism and colonization of Africa in practical ways by showing basic information like roads, terrain, natural resources, settlements, and communities.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Through this, maps made European commerce in Africa possible by showing potential commercial routes and made natural resource extraction possible by depicting locations of resources.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Such maps also enabled military conquests and made them more efficient, and imperial nations further used them to put their conquests on display.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] These same maps were then used to cement territorial claims, such as at the Berlin Conference of 1884–1885.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Before 1749, maps of the African continent had African kingdoms drawn with assumed or contrived boundaries, with unknown or unexplored areas having drawings of animals, imaginary physical geographic features, and descriptive texts.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] B. d'Anville created the first map of the African continent that had blank spaces to represent the unknown territory.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In understanding basic maps, the field of cartography can be divided into two general categories: general cartography and thematic cartography.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] General cartography involves those maps that are constructed for a general audience and thus contain a variety of features.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] General maps exhibit many reference and location systems and often are produced in a series.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] For example, the 1:24,000 scale topographic maps of the United States Geological Survey (USGS) are a standard as compared to the 1:50,000 scale Canadian maps.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The government of the UK produces the classic 1:50,000 (replacing the older 1 inch to 1 mile) "Ordnance Survey" maps of the entire UK and with a range of correlated larger- and smaller-scale maps of great detail.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Many private mapping companies have also produced thematic map series.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Thematic cartography involves maps of specific geographic themes, oriented toward specific audiences.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] A couple of examples might be a dot map showing corn production in Indiana or a shaded area map of Ohio counties, divided into numerical choropleth classes.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] As the volume of geographic data has exploded over the last century, thematic cartography has become increasingly useful and necessary to interpret spatial, cultural and social data.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] A third type of map is known as an "orienteering," or special purpose map.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] This type of map falls somewhere between thematic and general maps.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] They combine general map elements with thematic attributes in order to design a map with a specific audience in mind.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Oftentimes, the type of audience an orienteering map is made for is in a particular industry or occupation.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] An example of this kind of map would be a municipal utility map.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] A topographic map is primarily concerned with the topographic description of a place, including (especially in the 20th and 21st centuries) the use of contour lines showing elevation.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Terrain or relief can be shown in a variety of ways (see Cartographic relief depiction).
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In the present era, one of the most widespread and advanced methods used to form topographic maps is to use computer software to generate digital elevation models which show shaded relief.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Before such software existed, cartographers had to draw shaded relief by hand.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] One cartographer who is respected as a master of hand-drawn shaded relief is the Swiss professor Eduard Imhof whose efforts in hill shading were so influential that his method became used around the world despite it being so labor-intensive.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] A topological map is a very general type of map, the kind one might sketch on a napkin.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] It often disregards scale and detail in the interest of clarity of communicating specific route or relational information.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Beck's London Underground map is an iconic example.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Although the most widely used map of "The Tube," it preserves little of reality: it varies scale constantly and abruptly, it straightens curved tracks, and it contorts directions.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The only topography on it is the River Thames, letting the reader know whether a station is north or south of the river.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] That and the topology of station order and interchanges between train lines are all that is left of the geographic space.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Yet those are all a typical passenger wishes to know, so the map fulfills its purpose.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Modern technology, including advances in printing, the advent of geographic information systems and graphics software, and the Internet, has vastly simplified the process of map creation and increased the palette of design options available to cartographers.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] This has led to a decreased focus on production skill, and an increased focus on quality design, the attempt to craft maps that are both aesthetically pleasing and practically useful for their intended purposes.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Its purpose may be as broad as teaching the major physical and political features of the entire world, or as narrow as convincing a neighbor to move a fence.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The audience may be as broad as the general public or as narrow as a single person.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Mapmakers use design principles to guide them in constructing a map that is effective for its purpose and audience.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The cartographic process spans many stages, starting from conceiving the need for a map and extending all the way through its consumption by an audience.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Conception begins with a real or imagined environment.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] As the cartographer gathers information about the subject, they consider how that information is structured and how that structure should inform the map's design.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Next, the cartographers experiment with generalization, symbolization, typography, and other map elements to find ways to portray the information so that the map reader can interpret the map as intended.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Guided by these experiments, the cartographer settles on a design and creates the map, whether in physical or electronic form.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Once finished, the map is delivered to its audience.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The map reader interprets the symbols and patterns on the map to draw conclusions and perhaps to take action.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] By the spatial perspectives they provide, maps help shape how we view the world.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Designing a map involves bringing together a number of elements and making a large number of decisions.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The elements of design fall into several broad topics, each of which has its own theory, its own research agenda, and its own best practices.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] That said, there are synergistic effects between these elements, meaning that the overall design process is not just working on each element one at a time, but an iterative feedback process of adjusting each to achieve the desired gestalt.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Some maps contain deliberate errors or distortions, either as propaganda or as a "watermark" to help the copyright owner identify infringement if the error appears in competitors' maps.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The latter often come in the form of nonexistent, misnamed, or misspelled "trap streets".
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Other names and forms for this are paper towns, fictitious entries, and copyright easter eggs.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Another motive for deliberate errors is cartographic "vandalism": a mapmaker wishing to leave their mark on the work.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Mount Richard, for example, was a fictitious peak on the Rocky Mountains' continental divide that appeared on a Boulder County, Colorado map in the early 1970s.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] It is believed to be the work of draftsman Richard Ciacci.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] The fiction was not discovered until two years later.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] In Switzerland's official maps, mapmakers have hidden illustrations of a hiker, fish, marmot, and more for over a century.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] Sandy Island in New Caledonia is an example of a fictitious location that stubbornly survives, reappearing on new maps copied from older maps while being deleted from other new editions.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] With the emergence of the internet and Web mapping, technologies allow for the creation and distribution of maps by people without proper cartographic training are readily available.
[src:map-projections-viz/cartography] This has led to maps that ignore cartographic conventions and are potentially misleading.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] In cartography, a **map projection** is any of a broad set of transformations employed to represent the curved two-dimensional surface of a globe on a plane.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] In a map projection, coordinates, often expressed as latitude and longitude, of locations from the surface of the globe are transformed to coordinates on a plane.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Projection is a necessary step in creating a two-dimensional map and is one of the essential elements of cartography.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] All projections of a sphere on a plane necessarily distort the surface in some way.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Depending on the purpose of the map, some distortions are acceptable and others are not; therefore, different map projections exist in order to preserve some properties of the sphere-like body at the expense of other properties.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The study of map projections is primarily about the characterization of their distortions.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] There is no limit to the number of possible map projections.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] More generally, projections are considered in several fields of pure mathematics, including differential geometry, projective geometry, and manifolds.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] However, the term *map projection* refers specifically to a cartographic projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Despite the name's literal meaning, projection is not limited to perspective projections, such as those resulting from casting a shadow on a screen, or the rectilinear image produced by a pinhole camera on a flat film plate.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Rather, any mathematical function that transforms coordinates from the curved surface distinctly and smoothly to the plane is a projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Few projections in practical use are perspective.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Most of this article assumes that the surface to be mapped is that of a sphere.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The Earth and other large celestial bodies are generally better modeled as oblate spheroids, whereas small objects such as asteroids often have irregular shapes.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The surfaces of planetary bodies can be mapped even if they are too irregular to be modeled well with a sphere or ellipsoid.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The most well-known map projection is the Mercator projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] This map projection has the property of being conformal.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] However, it has been criticized throughout the 20th century for enlarging regions further from the equator.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] To contrast, equal-area projections such as the Sinusoidal projection and the Gall–Peters projection show the correct sizes of countries relative to each other, but distort angles.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The National Geographic Society and most atlases favor map projections that compromise between area and angular distortion, such as the Robinson projection and the Winkel tripel projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Map projections can be constructed to preserve some of these properties at the expense of others.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Because the Earth's curved surface is not isometric to a plane, preservation of shapes inevitably requires a variable scale and, consequently, non-proportional presentation of areas.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Similarly, an area-preserving projection can not be conformal, resulting in shapes and bearings distorted in most places of the map.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Each projection preserves, compromises, or approximates basic metric properties in different ways.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The purpose of the map determines which projection should form the base for the map.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Because maps have many different purposes, a diversity of projections have been created to suit those purposes.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Another consideration in the configuration of a projection is its compatibility with data sets to be used on the map.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Data sets are geographic information; their collection depends on the chosen datum (model) of the Earth.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Different datums assign slightly different coordinates to the same location, so in large scale maps, such as those from national mapping systems, it is important to match the datum to the projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The slight differences in coordinate assignation between different datums is not a concern for world maps or those of large regions, where such differences are reduced to imperceptibility.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Carl Friedrich Gauss's *Theorema Egregium* proved that a sphere's surface cannot be represented on a plane without distortion.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The same applies to other reference surfaces used as models for the Earth, such as oblate spheroids, ellipsoids, and geoids.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Since any map projection is a representation of one of those surfaces on a plane, all map projections distort.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The classical way of showing the distortion inherent in a projection is to use Tissot's indicatrix.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] For a given point, using the scale factor *h* along the meridian, the scale factor *k* along the parallel, and the angle *θ*′ between them, Nicolas Tissot described how to construct an ellipse that illustrates the amount and orientation of the components of distortion.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] By spacing the ellipses regularly along the meridians and parallels, the network of indicatrices shows how distortion varies across the map.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Many other ways have been described of showing the distortion in projections.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Like Tissot's indicatrix, the **Goldberg-Gott indicatrix** is based on infinitesimals, and depicts *flexion* and *skewness* (bending and lopsidedness) distortions.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Rather than the original (enlarged) infinitesimal circle as in Tissot's indicatrix, some visual methods project finite shapes that span a part of the map.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] For example, a small circle of fixed radius (e.g., 15 degrees angular radius).
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] In the first half of the 20th century, projecting a human head onto different projections was common to show how distortion varies across one projection as compared to another.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] In dynamic media, shapes of familiar coastlines and boundaries can be dragged across an interactive map to show how the projection distorts sizes and shapes according to position on the map.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Another way to visualize local distortion is through grayscale or color gradations whose shade represents the magnitude of the angular deformation or areal inflation.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Sometimes both are shown simultaneously by blending two colors to create a bivariate map.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] To measure distortion globally across areas instead of at just a single point necessarily involves choosing priorities to reach a compromise.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Some schemes use distance distortion as a proxy for the combination of angular deformation and areal inflation; such methods arbitrarily choose what paths to measure and how to weight them in order to yield a single result.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Transformation of geographic coordinates (longitude and latitude) to Cartesian (*x*,*y*) or polar (*r*, *θ*) plane coordinates.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] In large-scale maps, Cartesian coordinates normally have a simple relation to eastings and northings defined as a grid superimposed on the projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] In small-scale maps, eastings and northings are not meaningful, and grids are not superimposed.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Some of the simplest map projections are literal projections, as obtained by placing a light source at some definite point relative to the globe and projecting its features onto a specified surface.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Although most projections are not defined in this way, picturing the light source-globe model can be helpful in understanding the basic concept of a map projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] A surface that can be unfolded or unrolled into a plane or sheet without stretching, tearing or shrinking is called a *developable surface*.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The cylinder, cone and the plane are all developable surfaces.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The sphere and ellipsoid do not have developable surfaces, so any projection of them onto a plane will have to distort the image.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] One way of describing a projection is first to project from the Earth's surface to a developable surface such as a cylinder or cone, and then to unroll the surface into a plane.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] While the first step inevitably distorts some properties of the globe, the developable surface can then be unfolded without further distortion.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Once a choice is made between projecting onto a cylinder, cone, or plane, the **aspect** of the shape must be specified.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The aspect describes how the developable surface is placed relative to the globe: it may be *normal* (such that the surface's axis of symmetry coincides with the Earth's axis), *transverse* (at right angles to the Earth's axis) or *oblique* (any angle in between).
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The developable surface may also be either *tangent* or *secant* to the sphere or ellipsoid.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Tangent means the surface touches but does not slice through the globe; secant means the surface does slice through the globe.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Moving the developable surface away from contact with the globe never preserves or optimizes metric properties, so that possibility is not discussed further here.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Tangent and secant lines (*standard lines*) are represented undistorted.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] If these lines are a parallel of latitude, as in conical projections, it is called a *standard parallel*.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The *central meridian* is the meridian to which the globe is rotated before projecting.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The central meridian (usually written *λ*0) and a parallel of origin (usually written *φ*0) are often used to define the origin of the map projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] A globe is the only way to represent the Earth with constant scale throughout the entire map in all directions.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] A map cannot achieve that property for any area, no matter how small.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] It can, however, achieve constant scale along specific lines.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Projection construction is also affected by how the shape of the Earth or planetary body is approximated.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] In the following section on projection categories, the earth is taken as a sphere in order to simplify the discussion.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] However, the Earth's actual shape is closer to an oblate ellipsoid.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Whether spherical or ellipsoidal, the principles discussed hold without loss of generality.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Selecting a model for a shape of the Earth involves choosing between the advantages and disadvantages of a sphere versus an ellipsoid.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Spherical models are useful for small-scale maps such as world atlases and globes, since the error at that scale is not usually noticeable or important enough to justify using the more complicated ellipsoid.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The ellipsoidal model is commonly used to construct topographic maps and for other large- and medium-scale maps that need to accurately depict the land surface.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Auxiliary latitudes are often employed in projecting the ellipsoid.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] A third model is the geoid, a more complex and accurate representation of Earth's shape coincident with what mean sea level would be if there were no winds, tides, or land.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Compared to the best fitting ellipsoid, a geoidal model would change the characterization of important properties such as distance, conformality and equivalence.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Therefore, in geoidal projections that preserve such properties, the mapped graticule would deviate from a mapped ellipsoid's graticule.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Normally the geoid is not used as an Earth model for projections, however, because Earth's shape is very regular, with the undulation of the geoid amounting to less than 100 m from the ellipsoidal model out of the 6.3 million m Earth radius.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] For irregular planetary bodies such as asteroids, however, sometimes models analogous to the geoid are used to project maps from.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Other regular solids are sometimes used as generalizations for smaller bodies' geoidal equivalent.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] For example, Io is better modeled by triaxial ellipsoid or prolated spheroid with small eccentricities.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Haumea's shape is a Jacobi ellipsoid, with its major axis twice as long as its minor and with its middle axis one and half times as long as its minor.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] See map projection of the triaxial ellipsoid for further information.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] One way to classify map projections is based on the type of surface onto which the globe is projected.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The most common projection surfaces are cylindrical (e.g., Mercator), conic (e.g., Albers), and planar (e.g., stereographic).
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Many mathematical projections, however, do not neatly fit into any of these three projection methods.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Hence other peer categories have been described in the literature, such as pseudoconic, pseudocylindrical, pseudoazimuthal, retroazimuthal, and polyconic.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Another way to classify projections is according to properties of the model they preserve.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Because the sphere is not a developable surface, it is impossible to construct a map projection that is both equal-area and conformal.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The three developable surfaces (plane, cylinder, cone) provide useful models for understanding, describing, and developing map projections.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] However, these models are limited in two fundamental ways.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] For one thing, most world projections in use do not fall into any of those categories.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] For another thing, even most projections that do fall into those categories are not naturally attainable through physical projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Lee's objection refers to the way the terms *cylindrical*, *conic*, and *planar* (azimuthal) have been abstracted in the field of map projections.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] If maps were projected as in light shining through a globe onto a developable surface, then the spacing of parallels would follow a very limited set of possibilities.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Has parallels constrained to where they fall when light shines through the globe onto the cylinder, with the light source someplace along the line formed by the intersection of the prime meridian with the equator, and the center of the sphere.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] (If you rotate the globe before projecting then the parallels and meridians will not necessarily still be straight lines.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Where the light source emanates along the line described in this last constraint is what yields the differences between the various "natural" cylindrical projections.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] But the term *cylindrical* as used in the field of map projections relaxes the last constraint entirely.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Instead the parallels can be placed according to any algorithm the designer has decided suits the needs of the map.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The famous Mercator projection is one in which the placement of parallels does not arise by projection; instead parallels are placed how they need to be in order to satisfy the property that a course of constant bearing is always plotted as a straight line.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] A normal cylindrical projection is any projection in which meridians are mapped to equally spaced vertical lines and circles of latitude (parallels) are mapped to horizontal lines.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The mapping of meridians to vertical lines can be visualized by imagining a cylinder whose axis coincides with the Earth's axis of rotation.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] This cylinder is wrapped around the Earth, projected onto, and then unrolled.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] By the geometry of their construction, cylindrical projections stretch distances east-west.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The amount of stretch is the same at any chosen latitude on all cylindrical projections, and is given by the secant of the latitude as a multiple of the equator's scale.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] In the first case (Mercator), the east-west scale always equals the north-south scale.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] In the second case (central cylindrical), the north-south scale exceeds the east-west scale everywhere away from the equator.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Each remaining case has a pair of secant lines—a pair of identical latitudes of opposite sign (or else the equator) at which the east-west scale matches the north-south-scale.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Normal cylindrical projections map the whole Earth as a finite rectangle, except in the first two cases, where the rectangle stretches infinitely tall while retaining constant width.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] A transverse cylindrical projection is a cylindrical projection that in the tangent case uses a great circle along a meridian as contact line for the cylinder.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] An oblique cylindrical projection aligns with a great circle, but not the equator and not a meridian.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Pseudocylindrical projections represent the *central* meridian as a straight line segment.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Other meridians are longer than the central meridian and bow outward, away from the central meridian.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Pseudocylindrical projections map parallels as straight lines.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Along parallels, each point from the surface is mapped at a distance from the central meridian that is proportional to its difference in longitude from the central meridian.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Therefore, meridians are equally spaced along a given parallel.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] On a pseudocylindrical map, any point further from the equator than some other point has a higher latitude than the other point, preserving north-south relationships.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] This trait is useful when illustrating phenomena that depend on latitude, such as climate.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The HEALPix projection combines an equal-area cylindrical projection in equatorial regions with the Collignon projection in polar areas.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The term *conic projection* is used to refer to any projection in which meridians are mapped to equally spaced lines radiating out from the apex and circles of latitude (parallels) are mapped to circular arcs centered on the apex.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] When making a conic map, the map maker arbitrarily picks two standard parallels.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Those standard parallels may be visualized as secant lines where the cone intersects the globe—or, if the map maker chooses the same parallel twice, as the tangent line where the cone is tangent to the globe.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The resulting conic map has low distortion in scale, shape, and area near those standard parallels.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Distances along the parallels to the north of both standard parallels or to the south of both standard parallels are stretched; distances along parallels between the standard parallels are compressed.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] When a single standard parallel is used, distances along all other parallels are stretched.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Azimuthal projections have the property that directions from a central point are preserved and therefore great circles through the central point are represented by straight lines on the map.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The mapping of radial lines can be visualized by imagining a plane tangent to the Earth, with the central point as tangent point.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The radial scale is *r′*(*d*) and the transverse scale *r*(*d*)/(*R* sin ⁠*d*/*R*⁠) where *R* is the radius of the Earth.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Polyhedral map projections use a polyhedron to subdivide the globe into faces, and then projects each face to the globe.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The most well-known polyhedral map projection is Buckminster Fuller's Dymaxion map.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Conformal, or orthomorphic, map projections preserve angles locally, implying that they map infinitesimal circles of constant size anywhere on the Earth to infinitesimal circles of varying sizes on the map.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] In contrast, mappings that are not conformal distort most such small circles into ellipses of distortion.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] An important consequence of conformality is that relative angles at each point of the map are correct, and the local scale (although varying throughout the map) in every direction around any one point is constant.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Equal-area maps preserve area measure, generally distorting shapes in order to do so.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Equal-area maps are also called *equivalent* or *authalic*.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] If the length of the line segment connecting two projected points on the plane is proportional to the geodesic distance between the two unprojected points on the globe, then we say that distance has been preserved between those two points.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] An **equidistant projection** preserves distances from one or two special points to all other points.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The special point or points may get stretched into a line or curve segment when projected.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] In that case, the point on the line or curve segment closest to the point being measured to must be used to measure the distance.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Compromise projections give up the idea of perfectly preserving metric properties, seeking instead to strike a balance between distortions, or to simply make things look right.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Most of these types of projections distort shape in the polar regions more than at the equator.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The mathematics of projection do not permit any particular map projection to be best for everything.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Thus, many projections exist to serve the many uses of maps and their vast range of scales.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Modern national mapping systems typically employ a transverse Mercator or close variant for large-scale maps in order to preserve conformality and low variation in scale over small areas.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] For smaller-scale maps, such as those spanning continents or the entire world, many projections are in common use according to their fitness for the purpose, such as Winkel tripel, Robinson and Mollweide.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Reference maps of the world often appear on compromise projections.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Due to distortions inherent in any map of the world, the choice of projection becomes largely one of aesthetics.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] Thematic maps normally require an equal area projection so that phenomena per unit area are shown in correct proportion.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] However, representing area ratios correctly necessarily distorts shapes more than many maps that are not equal-area.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] The Mercator projection, developed for navigational purposes, has often been used in world maps where other projections would have been more appropriate.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] This problem has long been recognized even outside professional circles.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] A controversy in the 1980s over the Peters map motivated the American Cartographic Association (now the Cartography and Geographic Information Society) to produce a series of booklets (including *Which Map Is Best*) designed to educate the public about map projections and distortion in maps.
[src:map-projections-viz/map-projection] In 1989 and 1990, after some internal debate, seven North American geographic organizations adopted a resolution recommending against using any rectangular projection (including Mercator and Gall–Peters) for reference maps of the world.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The **Mercator projection** (/mərˈkeɪtər/) is a conformal cylindrical map projection first presented by Flemish geographer and mapmaker Gerardus Mercator in 1569.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] In the 18th century, it became the standard map projection for navigation due to its property of representing rhumb lines as straight lines.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] When applied to world maps, the Mercator projection inflates the size of lands the farther they are from the equator.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Therefore, landmasses such as Greenland and Antarctica appear far larger than they actually are relative to landmasses near the equator.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Its use for maps other than marine charts declined throughout the 20th century, but resurged in the 21st century due to characteristics favorable for World-Wide-Web maps.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] German polymath Erhard Etzlaub engraved miniature "compass maps" (about 10×8 cm) of Europe and parts of Africa that spanned latitudes 0°–67° to allow adjustment of his portable pocket-size sundials.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The projection found on these maps, dating to 1511, was stated by John Snyder in 1987 to be the same projection as Mercator's.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] However, given the geometry of a sundial, these maps may well have been based on the similar central cylindrical projection, a limiting case of the gnomonic projection, which is the basis for a sundial.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Snyder amended his assessment to "a similar projection" in 1993.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Portuguese mathematician and cosmographer Pedro Nunes first described the mathematical principle of the rhumb line or loxodrome, a path with constant bearing as measured relative to true north, which can be used in marine navigation to pick which compass bearing to follow.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] In 1537, he proposed constructing a nautical atlas composed of several large-scale sheets in the equirectangular projection as a way to minimize distortion of directions.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] If these sheets were brought to the same scale and assembled, they would approximate the Mercator projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] In 1541, Flemish geographer and mapmaker Gerardus Mercator included a network of rhumb lines on a terrestrial globe he made for Nicolas Perrenot.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] In 1569, Mercator announced a new projection by publishing a large world map measuring 202 by 124 cm (80 by 49 in) and printed in eighteen separate sheets.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Mercator titled the map *Nova et Aucta Orbis Terrae Descriptio ad Usum Navigantium Emendata*: "A new and augmented description of Earth corrected for the use of sailors".
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] This title, along with an elaborate explanation for using the projection that appears as a section of text on the map, shows that Mercator understood exactly what he had achieved and that he intended the projection to aid navigation.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Mercator never explained the method of construction or how he arrived at it.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Various hypotheses have been tendered over the years, but in any case Mercator's friendship with Pedro Nunes and his access to the loxodromic tables Nunes created likely aided his efforts.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] English mathematician Edward Wright published the first accurate tables for constructing the projection in 1599 and, in more detail, in 1610, calling his treatise "Certaine Errors in Navigation".
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The first mathematical formulation was publicized around 1645 by a mathematician named Henry Bond (c.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] However, the mathematics involved were developed but never published by mathematician Thomas Harriot starting around 1589.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The development of the Mercator projection represented a major breakthrough in the nautical cartography of the 16th century.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] However, it was much ahead of its time, since the old navigational and surveying techniques were not compatible with its use in navigation.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Two main problems prevented its immediate application: the impossibility of determining the longitude at sea with adequate accuracy and the fact that magnetic directions, instead of geographical directions, were used in navigation.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Only in the middle of the 18th century, after the marine chronometer was invented and the spatial distribution of magnetic declination was known, could the Mercator projection be fully adopted by navigators.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Despite those position-finding limitations, the Mercator projection can be found in many world maps in the centuries following Mercator's first publication.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] However, it did not begin to dominate world maps until the 19th century, when the problem of position determination had been largely solved.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Once the Mercator became the usual projection for commercial and educational maps, it came under persistent criticism from cartographers for its unbalanced representation of landmasses and its inability to usefully show the polar regions.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The criticisms leveled against inappropriate use of the Mercator projection resulted in a flurry of new inventions in the late 19th and early 20th century, often directly touted as alternatives to the Mercator.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Due to these pressures, publishers gradually reduced their use of the projection over the course of the 20th century.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] However, the advent of Web mapping gave the projection an abrupt resurgence in the form of the Web Mercator projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Today, the Mercator can be found in marine charts, occasional world maps, and Web mapping services, but commercial atlases have largely abandoned it, and wall maps of the world can be found in many alternative projections.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Google Maps, which relied on it since 2005, still uses it for local-area maps but dropped the projection from desktop platforms in 2017 for maps that are zoomed out of local areas.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Many other online mapping services still exclusively use the Web Mercator.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Afterward, this cylinder is unrolled onto a flat plane to make a map.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] In this interpretation, the scale of the surface is preserved exactly along the circle where the cylinder touches the sphere, but increases nonlinearly for points further from the contact circle.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] This is sometimes visualized as a projection onto a cylinder which is *secant* to (cuts) the sphere, though this picture is misleading insofar as the standard parallels are not spaced the same distance apart on the map as the shortest distance between them through the interior of the sphere.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The original and most common aspect of the Mercator projection for maps of Earth is the normal aspect, for which the axis of the cylinder is Earth's axis of rotation which passes through the North and South poles, and the contact circle is Earth's equator.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] As for all cylindrical projections in normal aspect, circles of latitude and meridians of longitude are straight and perpendicular to each other on the map, forming a grid of rectangles.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] While circles of latitude on Earth are smaller the closer they are to the poles, they are stretched in an East–West direction to have uniform length on any cylindrical map projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Among cylindrical projections, the Mercator projection is the unique projection which balances this East–West stretching by a precisely corresponding North–South stretching, so that at every location the scale is locally uniform and angles are preserved.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Because the linear scale of a Mercator map in normal aspect increases with latitude, it distorts the size of geographical objects far from the equator and conveys a distorted perception of the overall geometry of the planet.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] At latitudes greater than 70° north or south, the Mercator projection is practically unusable, because the linear scale becomes infinitely large at the poles.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] A Mercator map can therefore never fully show the polar areas (but see Uses below for applications of the oblique and transverse Mercator projections).
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The Mercator projection is often compared to and confused with the central cylindrical projection, which is the result of projecting points from the sphere onto a tangent cylinder along straight radial lines, as if from a light source placed at Earth's center.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Both have extreme distortion far from the equator and cannot show the poles.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] However, they are different projections and have different properties.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] As with all map projections, the shapes or sizes are distortions of the true layout of Earth's surface.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The Mercator projection exaggerates areas far from the equator; the closer to Earth's poles, the greater the distortion.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Because of great land area distortions, critics like George Kellaway and Irving Fisher consider the projection unsuitable for general world maps.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] It has been conjectured to have influenced people's views of the world: because it shows countries near the Equator as too small when compared to those of Europe and North America, it has been supposed to cause people to consider those countries as less important.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The areal exaggerations of the Mercator projection were suspected to have fuelled Donald Trump's attempt to annex Greenland in 2025, particularly in light of Trump's previous exclamation that "I love maps.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] And I always said, 'Look at the size of this.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Mercator himself used the equal-area sinusoidal projection to show relative areas.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] However, despite such criticisms, the Mercator projection was, especially in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, perhaps the most common projection used in world maps.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Atlases largely stopped using the Mercator projection for world maps or for areas distant from the equator in the 1940s, preferring other cylindrical projections, or forms of equal-area projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The Mercator projection is, however, still commonly used for areas near the equator where distortion is minimal.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] It is also frequently found in maps of time zones.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Arno Peters stirred controversy beginning in 1972 when he proposed what is now usually called the Gall–Peters projection to remedy the problems of the Mercator, claiming it to be his own original work without referencing prior work by cartographers such as Gall's work from 1855.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The projection he promoted is a specific parameterization of the cylindrical equal-area projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] In response, a 1989 resolution by seven North American geographical groups disparaged using cylindrical projections for general-purpose world maps, which would include both the Mercator and the Gall–Peters.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] As of 2025 the African Union supports a campaign favoring the Equal Earth projection over the Mercator projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Practically every marine chart in print is based on the Mercator projection due to its uniquely favorable properties for navigation.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] It is also commonly used by street map services hosted on the Internet, due to its uniquely favorable properties for local-area maps computed on demand.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Mercator projections were also important in the mathematical development of plate tectonics in the 1960s.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The Mercator projection was designed for use in marine navigation because of its unique property of representing any course of constant bearing as a straight segment.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Such a course, known as a rhumb (alternately called a rhumb line or loxodrome) is preferred in marine navigation because ships can sail in a constant compass direction.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] This reduces the difficult, error-prone course corrections that otherwise would be necessary when sailing a different course.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] For small distances (compared to the radius of Earth), the difference between the rhumb and the great circle course is negligible.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Even for longer distances, the simplicity of the constant bearing makes it attractive.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] As observed by Mercator, on such a course the ship would not arrive by the shortest route but it will surely arrive.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Sailing a rhumb meant that all that the sailors had to do was keep a constant course as long as they knew where they were when they started, where they intended to be when they finished, and had a map in Mercator projection that correctly showed those two coordinates.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Many major online street mapping services (Bing Maps, Google Maps, Mapbox, MapQuest, OpenStreetMap, Yahoo!
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Maps, and others) use a variant of the Mercator projection for their map images called Web Mercator or Google Web Mercator.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Despite its obvious scale variation at the world level (small scales), the projection is well-suited as an interactive world map that can be zoomed seamlessly to local (large-scale) maps, where there is relatively little distortion due to the variant projection's near-conformality.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The major online street mapping services' tiling systems display most of the world at the lowest zoom level as a single square image, excluding the polar regions by truncation at latitudes of *φ*max = ±85.05113°.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] (See below.) Latitude values outside this range are mapped using a different relationship that does not diverge at *φ* = ±90°.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] A transverse Mercator projection tilts the cylinder axis so that it is perpendicular to Earth's axis.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The tangent standard line then coincides with a meridian and its opposite meridian, giving a constant scale factor along those meridians, and a near-constant one within a band of a few degrees of longitude around them.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] This property makes such a projection useful for mapping regions that are either compact or predominately north–south in extent.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] In its more complex ellipsoidal form, most national grid systems around the world use the transverse Mercator, as does the Universal Transverse Mercator coordinate system.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] An oblique Mercator projection tilts the cylinder axis away from Earth's axis to an angle of one's choosing, so that its tangent or secant lines of contact are circles that are also tilted relative to Earth's parallels of latitude.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Practical uses for the oblique projection, such as national grid systems, use ellipsoidal developments of the oblique Mercator in order to keep scale variation low along the surface projection of the cylinder's axis.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The animation below shows a continuous transformation between the normal Mercator projection and the transverse projection, running through the intermediate oblique states.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] A rhumb line (blue) and great circle (red) from Tokyo, Japan, to Callao, Peru, change according to the projection's aspect.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The rhumb between them is straight only on the normal projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] On one of the intermediate oblique projections, the great-circle path between the two cities is straight.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] In this plot the y-axis is always the projected axis of the cylinder.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The sphere is rotated inside the cylinder to change aspect.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Initially the axis is normal to the equator (projected as the thick green line) but ends transverse to it, when the projected equator extends to infinity in the vertical direction.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] where ⁠ R ⁠ is an arbitrary scale factor which determines the size of the resulting map, ln is the natural logarithm, and tan is the trigonometric tangent function.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Although the surface of Earth is better modelled by an oblate ellipsoid of revolution, for small scale maps the ellipsoid is approximated by a sphere of radius *a*, where *a* is approximately 6,371 km.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] This spherical approximation of Earth can be modelled by a smaller sphere of radius *R*, called the *globe* in this section.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The globe determines the scale of the map.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The various cylindrical projections specify how the geographic detail is transferred from the globe to a cylinder tangential to it at the equator.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The cylinder is then unrolled to give the planar map.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The fraction ⁠*R*/*a*⁠ is called the representative fraction (RF) or the principal scale of the projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] A cylindrical map projection is specified by formulae linking the geographic coordinates of latitude *φ* and longitude *λ* to Cartesian coordinates on the map with origin on the equator and *x*-axis along the equator.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] By construction, all points on the same meridian lie on the same *generator* of the cylinder at a constant value of *x*, but the distance *y* along the generator (measured from the equator) is an arbitrary function of latitude, *y*(*φ*).
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] In general this function does not describe the geometrical projection (as of light rays onto a screen) from the centre of the globe to the cylinder, which is only one of an unlimited number of ways to conceptually project a cylindrical map.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Since the cylinder is tangential to the globe at the equator, the scale factor between globe and cylinder is unity on the equator but nowhere else.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] In particular since the radius of a parallel, or circle of latitude, is *R* cos *φ*, the corresponding parallel on the map must have been stretched by a factor of ⁠1/cos *φ*⁠ = sec *φ*.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] This scale factor on the parallel is conventionally denoted by *k* and the corresponding scale factor on the meridian is denoted by *h*.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] One implication of that is the "isotropy of scale factors", which means that the point scale factor is independent of direction, so that small shapes are preserved by the projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] This implies that the vertical scale factor, *h*, equals the horizontal scale factor, *k*.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The graph shows the variation of this scale factor with latitude.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The area scale factor is the product of the parallel and meridian scales *hk* = sec2*φ*.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] For Greenland, taking 73° as a median latitude, *hk* = 11.7.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] For Australia, taking 25° as a median latitude, *hk* = 1.2.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] For Great Britain, taking 55° as a median latitude, *hk* = 3.04.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The variation with latitude is sometimes indicated by multiple bar scales as shown below.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The classic way of showing the distortion inherent in a projection is to use Tissot's indicatrix.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Nicolas Tissot noted that the scale factors at a point on a map projection, specified by the numbers *h* and *k*, define an ellipse at that point.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] For cylindrical projections, the axes of the ellipse are aligned to the meridians and parallels.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] For the Mercator projection, *h* = *k*, so the ellipses degenerate into circles with radius proportional to the value of the scale factor for that latitude.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] These circles are rendered on the projected map with extreme variation in size, indicative of Mercator's scale variations.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] As discussed above, the isotropy condition implies that ⁠ $h=k=\sec \varphi$ ⁠.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Consider a point on the globe of radius ⁠ R ⁠ with longitude ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ and latitude ⁠ $\varphi$ ⁠, expressed in radians.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] If ⁠ $\varphi$ ⁠ is increased by an infinitesimal amount ⁠ $d\varphi$ ⁠, the point moves ⁠ $R\,d\varphi$ ⁠ along a meridian of the globe of radius ⁠ R ⁠, so the corresponding change in ⁠ y ⁠ is ⁠ $dy=hR\,d\varphi =R\sec \varphi \,d\varphi$ ⁠.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Therefore ⁠ $y'(\varphi )=R\sec \varphi$ ⁠.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Similarly, increasing ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ by ⁠ $d\lambda$ ⁠ moves the point ⁠ $R\cos \varphi \,d\lambda$ ⁠ along a parallel of the globe, so ⁠ $dx=kR\cos \varphi \,d\lambda =Rd\lambda$ ⁠.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The value ⁠ $\lambda _{0}$ ⁠ is the longitude of an arbitrary central meridian, often the prime meridian ⁠ $\lambda _{0}=0$ ⁠.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The vertical coordinate ⁠ y ⁠ was historically called the *meridional part* of ⁠ $\varphi$ ⁠.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] In the figure, ⁠ y ⁠ is plotted against ⁠ $\varphi$ ⁠ for the case ⁠ $R=1$ ⁠, such that it equals the anti-gudermannian of ⁠ $\varphi$ ⁠; it tends to infinity at the poles.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The numerical value of ⁠ y ⁠ is not usually shown on printed maps; some maps show a non-linear scale of latitudes, but more often than not maps show only a graticule of selected meridians and parallels.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] As a conformal map, the Mercator projection can be conveniently expressed using a single complex number to represent each point on the sphere rather than a pair of real-number coordinates.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The complex number representing each point on this so-called Riemann sphere is found by conformally mapping the sphere onto the complex plane via the stereographic projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] From there, the Mercator projection is just the complex logarithm, ⁠ $z\mapsto \log z$ ⁠, a conformal map of the complex plane (with the exception of the origin, whose logarithm is undefined) onto a two-infinite-ended cylinder.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Starting from geographic coordinates ⁠ $(\lambda ,\varphi )$ ⁠ in radians, the stereographic projection yields a complex number ⁠ $\textstyle z=e^{\lambda i}\tan {\bigl (}{\tfrac {1}{4}}\pi -{\tfrac {1}{2}}\varphi {\bigr )}$ ⁠, with the North Pole mapped to the origin.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The imaginary part of the resulting complex number represents the longitude and its real part represents the negative projected latitude.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] To better match prevailing conventions about the plotting of complex numbers and world maps it can be rotated a quarter turn and scaled arbitrarily by multiplying by a scaling factor ⁠ $-Ri$ ⁠.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Finding the longitude as an inverse of the ⁠ x ⁠ coordinate is trivial.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The latitude can be found as an inverse of ⁠ y ⁠ as the gudermannian of ⁠ $y/R$ ⁠.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] There are many identities relating the circular angle ⁠ $\varphi$ ⁠ to its anti-gudermannian ⁠ $\operatorname {gd} ^{-1}\varphi =y/R$ ⁠, a hyperbolic angle, which can be used to construct alternate expressions for the functions from one to the other.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] where sinh is the hyperbolic sine function.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] where tanh is the hyperbolic tangent function.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The above formulae are written in terms of the globe radius ⁠ R ⁠.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] It is often convenient to work directly with the map width ⁠ W ⁠, in terms of which, assuming the map shows the whole globe, ⁠ $R=W/2\pi$ ⁠.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The ordinate *y* of the Mercator projection becomes infinite at the poles and the map must be truncated at some latitude less than ninety degrees.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Mercator's original map is truncated at 80°N and 66°S with the result that European countries were moved toward the centre of the map.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Even more extreme truncations have been used: a Finnish school atlas was truncated at approximately 76°N and 56°S, an aspect ratio of 1.97.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Much Web-based mapping uses a zoomable version of the Mercator projection with an aspect ratio of one.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] In this case the maximum latitude attained must correspond to *y* = ±⁠*W*/2⁠, or equivalently ⁠*y*/*R*⁠ = π.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The relations between *y*(*φ*) and properties of the projection, such as the transformation of angles and the variation in scale, follow from the geometry of corresponding *small* elements on the globe and map.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The figure below shows a point P at latitude *φ* and longitude *λ* on the globe and a nearby point Q at latitude *φ* + *δφ* and longitude *λ* + *δλ*.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The vertical lines PK and MQ are arcs of meridians of length *Rδφ*.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The horizontal lines PM and KQ are arcs of parallels of length *R*(cos *φ*)*δλ*.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The corresponding points on the projection define a rectangle of width *δx* and height *δy*.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Since the meridians are mapped to lines of constant *x*, we must have *x* = *R*(*λ* − *λ*0) and *δx* = *Rδλ*, (*λ* in radians).
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] In the case of the Mercator projection, *y'*(*φ*) = *R* sec *φ*, so this gives us *h* = *k* and *α* = *β*.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The fact that *h* = *k* is the isotropy of scale factors discussed above.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The fact that *α* = *β* reflects another implication of the mapping being conformal, namely the fact that a sailing course of constant azimuth on the globe is mapped into the same constant grid bearing on the map.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Converting ruler distance on the Mercator map into true (great circle) distance on the sphere is straightforward along the equator, but not at other latitudes.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] One problem is the variation of scale with latitude.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Another problem is that straight lines on the map (rhumb lines), other than the meridians or the equator, do not correspond to great circles.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The distinction between rhumb (sailing) distance and great circle (true) distance was understood by Mercator.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] (See Legend 12 on the 1569 map.) He asserted that the rhumb line distance is an acceptable approximation for true great circle distance for courses of short or moderate distance, particularly at lower latitudes.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] He quantified his statement: "When the great circle distances which are to be measured in the vicinity of the equator do not exceed 20 degrees of a great circle, or 15 degrees near Spain and France, or 8 and even 10 degrees in northern parts it is convenient to use rhumb line distances".
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] With radius and great circle circumference equal to 6,371 km and 40,030 km respectively an RF of ⁠1/300M⁠, for which *R* = 2.12 cm and *W* = 13.34 cm, implies that a ruler measurement of 3 mm. in any direction from a point on the equator corresponds to approximately 900 km.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The corresponding distances for latitudes 20°, 40°, 60° and 80° are 846 km, 689 km, 450 km and 156 km respectively.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Longer distances require various approaches.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Scale is unity on the equator (for a non-secant projection).
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] For the above model, with RF = ⁠1/300M⁠, 1 cm corresponds to 3,000 km.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] For the above model 1 cm corresponds to 1,500 km at a latitude of 60°.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] This is not the shortest distance between the chosen endpoints on the parallel because a parallel is not a great circle.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The difference is small for short distances but increases as *λ*, the longitudinal separation, increases.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] For two points, A and B, separated by 10° of longitude on the parallel at 60° the distance along the parallel is approximately 0.5 km greater than the great circle distance.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] (The distance AB along the parallel is (*a* cos *φ*) *λ*.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The length of the chord AB is 2(*a* cos *φ*) sin ⁠*λ*/2⁠.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] On the other hand, the geodesic between these points is a great circle arc through the pole subtending an angle of 60° at the center: the length of this arc is one sixth of the great circle circumference, about 6,672 km.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The difference is 3,338 km so the ruler distance measured from the map is quite misleading even after correcting for the latitude variation of the scale factor.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] A meridian of the map is a great circle on the globe but the continuous scale variation means ruler measurement alone cannot yield the true distance between distant points on the meridian.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] If the latitudes of the end points cannot be determined with confidence then they can be found instead by calculation on the ruler distance.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] where *R* may be calculated from the width *W* of the map by *R* = ⁠*W*/2π⁠.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] For example, on a map with *R* = 1 the values of *y* = 0, 1, 2, 3 correspond to latitudes of *φ* = 0°, 50°, 75°, 84° and therefore the successive intervals of 1 cm on the map correspond to latitude intervals on the globe of 50°, 25°, 9° and distances of 5,560 km, 2,780 km, and 1,000 km on Earth.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] A straight line on the Mercator map at angle *α* to the meridians is a rhumb line.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] When *α* = ⁠π/2⁠ or ⁠3π/2⁠ the rhumb corresponds to one of the parallels; only one, the equator, is a great circle.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] When *α* = 0 or π it corresponds to a meridian great circle (if continued around the globe).
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] For all other values it is a spiral from pole to pole on the globe intersecting all meridians at the same angle, and is thus not a great circle.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] This section discusses only the last of these cases.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] If *α* is neither 0 nor π then the above figure of the infinitesimal elements shows that the length of an infinitesimal rhumb line on the sphere between latitudes *φ*; and *φ* + *δφ* is *a* sec *α* *δφ*.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Once again, if Δ*φ* may be read directly from an accurate latitude scale on the map, then the rhumb distance between map points with latitudes *φ*1 and *φ*2 is given by the above.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] These formulae give rhumb distances on the sphere which may differ greatly from true distances whose determination requires more sophisticated calculations.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] When Earth is modelled by a spheroid (ellipsoid of revolution) the Mercator projection must be modified if it is to remain conformal.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The scale factor *k* is unity on the equator, as it must be since the cylinder is tangential to the ellipsoid at the equator.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The ellipsoidal correction of the scale factor increases with latitude but it is never greater than *e*2, a correction of less than 1%.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The value of *e*2 is about 0.006 for all reference ellipsoids.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] This is much smaller than the scale inaccuracy, except very close to the equator.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] Only accurate Mercator projections of regions near the equator will necessitate the ellipsoidal corrections.
[src:map-projections-viz/mercator-projection] The inverse is solved iteratively, as the isometric latitude is involved.
[src:map-projections-viz/robinson-projection] The **Robinson projection** is a map projection of a world map that shows the entire world at once.
[src:map-projections-viz/robinson-projection] It was created in an attempt to find a good compromise to the problem of readily showing the whole globe as a flat image.
[src:map-projections-viz/robinson-projection] The Robinson projection was devised by Arthur H.
[src:map-projections-viz/robinson-projection] Robinson in 1963 in response to an appeal from the Rand McNally company, which has used the projection in general-purpose world maps since that time.
[src:map-projections-viz/robinson-projection] Robinson published details of the projection's construction in 1974.
[src:map-projections-viz/robinson-projection] The National Geographic Society (NGS) began using the Robinson projection for general-purpose, full world maps in 1988, replacing the Van der Grinten projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/robinson-projection] In 1998, the NGS abandoned the Robinson projection for that use in favor of the Winkel tripel projection, as the latter "reduces the distortion of land masses as they near the poles".
[src:map-projections-viz/robinson-projection] The Robinson projection is neither equal-area nor conformal, abandoning both for a compromise.
[src:map-projections-viz/robinson-projection] The creator felt that this produced a better overall view than could be achieved by adhering to either.
[src:map-projections-viz/robinson-projection] The meridians curve gently, avoiding extremes, but thereby stretch the poles into long lines instead of leaving them as points.
[src:map-projections-viz/robinson-projection] Hence, distortion close to the poles is severe, but quickly declines to moderate levels moving away from them.
[src:map-projections-viz/robinson-projection] The straight parallels imply severe angular distortion at the high latitudes toward the outer edges of the map – a fault inherent in any pseudocylindrical projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/robinson-projection] However, at the time it was developed, the projection effectively met Rand McNally's goal to produce appealing depictions of the entire world.
[src:map-projections-viz/robinson-projection] The table is indexed by latitude at 5-degree intervals; intermediate values are calculated using interpolation.
[src:map-projections-viz/robinson-projection] Robinson did not specify any particular interpolation method, but it is reported that others used either Aitken interpolation (with polynomials of unknown degrees) or cubic splines while analyzing area deformation on the Robinson projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/robinson-projection] The *X* column is the ratio of the length of the parallel to the length of the equator; the *Y* column can be multiplied by 0.2536 to obtain the ratio of the distance of that parallel from the equator to the length of the equator.
[src:map-projections-viz/robinson-projection] ${\begin{aligned}x&=0.8487\,RX(\lambda -\lambda _{0}),\\y&=1.3523\,RY,\end{aligned}}$ where *R* is the radius of the globe at the scale of the map, *λ* is the longitude of the point to plot, and *λ*0 is the central meridian chosen for the map (both *λ* and *λ*0 are expressed in radians).
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] It is the geometry that results from projecting a circle of infinitesimal radius from a curved geometric model, such as a globe, onto a map.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Tissot proved that the resulting diagram is an ellipse whose axes indicate the two principal directions along which scale is maximal and minimal at that point on the map.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] A single indicatrix describes the distortion at a single point.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Because distortion varies across a map, generally Tissot's indicatrices are placed across a map to illustrate the spatial change in distortion.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] A common scheme places them at each intersection of displayed meridians and parallels.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] These schematics are important in the study of map projections, both to illustrate distortion and to provide the basis for the calculations that represent the magnitude of distortion precisely at each point.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Because the infinitesimal circles represented by the ellipses on the map all have the same area on the underlying curved geometric model, the distortion imposed by the map projection is evident.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] There is a one-to-one correspondence between the Tissot indicatrix and the metric tensor of the map projection coordinate conversion.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Tissot's theory was developed in the context of cartographic analysis.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Generally the geometric model represents the Earth, and comes in the form of a sphere or ellipsoid.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] In conformal maps, where each point preserves angles projected from the geometric model, the Tissot's indicatrices are all circles of size varying by location, possibly also with varying orientation (given the four circle quadrants split by meridians and parallels).
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] In equal-area projections, where area proportions between objects are conserved, the Tissot's indicatrices all have the same area, though their shapes and orientations vary with location.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] In arbitrary projections, both area and shape vary across the map.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] In the diagram below, the circle $ABCD$ has unit area as defined on the surface of a sphere.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] The ellipse ${A'B'C'D'}$ is the Tissot's indicatrix that results from some projection of $ABCD$ onto a plane.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Linear scale has not been preserved in this projection, as ${OA'\ncong OA}$ and $OB'\ncong OB$ .
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Because ${\angle M'OA'\ncong \angle MOA}$ , we know that there is an angular distortion.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Because $\operatorname {Area} (A'B'C'D')\neq \operatorname {Area} (ABCD)$ , we know there is an areal distortion.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] The original circle in the above example had a radius of 1, but when dealing with a Tissot indicatrix, one deals with ellipses of infinitesimal radius.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Even though the radii of the original circle and its distortion ellipse will all be infinitesimal, by employing differential calculus the ratios between them can still be meaningfully calculated.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] For example, if the ratio between the radius of the input circle and a projected circle is equal to 1, then the indicatrix is drawn with as a circle with an area of 1.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] The size that the indicatrix gets drawn on the map is arbitrary: they are all scaled by the same factor so that their sizes are proportional to one another.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Like M in the diagram, the axes from O along the parallel and along the meridian may undergo a change of length and a rotation during projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] For a given point, it is common in the literature to represent the scale along the meridian as h and the scale along the parallel as k .
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Unless the projection is conformal, all angles except the one subtended by the semi-major axis and semi-minor axis of the ellipse may have changed as well.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] A particular angle will have changed the most, and the value of that maximum change is known as the angular deformation, denoted as $\theta$ .
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] In general, which angle that is and how it is oriented do not figure prominently into distortion analysis; it is the magnitude of the change that is significant.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] where $\varphi$ and $\lambda$ are the latitude and longitude coordinates of a point, R is the radius of the globe, and x and y are the point's resulting coordinates after projection.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] In the result for any given point, a and b are the maximum and minimum scale factors, analogous to the semimajor and semiminor axes in the diagram; s represents the amount of inflation or deflation in area, and $\omega$ represents the maximum angular distortion.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] For conformal projections such as the Mercator projection, $h=k$ and $\theta ={\pi \over 2}$ , such that at each point the ellipse degenerates into a circle, with the radius being equal to the scale factor.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] For equal-area such as the sinusoidal projection, the semi-major axis of the ellipse is the reciprocal of the semi-minor axis, such that every ellipse has equal area even as their eccentricities vary.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] For arbitrary projections, the shape and the area of the ellipses at each point are largely independent from one another.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Another way to understand and derive Tissot's indicatrix is through the differential geometry of surfaces.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] This approach lends itself well to modern numerical methods, as the parameters of Tissot's indicatrix can be computed using singular value decomposition (SVD) and central difference approximation.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] This result relates the measure of distance on the ellipsoid surface as a function of the spherical coordinate system.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Recall that the purpose of Tissot's indicatrix is to relate how distances on the sphere change when mapped to a planar surface.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Specifically, the desired relation is the transform ${\mathcal {T}}$ that relates differential distance along the bases of the spherical coordinate system to differential distance along the bases of the Cartesian coordinate system on the planar map.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] where $ds(\lambda ,0)$ and $ds(0,\phi )$ represent the computation of $ds$ along the longitudinal and latitudinal axes, respectively.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Now, in order to relate the distances on the ellipsoid surface to those on the plane, we need to relate the coordinate systems.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] This transform ${\mathcal {T}}$ encapsulates the mapping from the ellipsoid surface to the plane.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Expressed in this form, SVD can be used to parcel out the important components of the local transformation.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] In order to extract the desired distortion information, at any given location in the spherical coordinate system, the values of K can be computed directly.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] The Jacobian, J , can be computed analytically from the mapping function itself, but it is often simpler to numerically approximate the values at any location on the map using central differences.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Once these values are computed, SVD can be applied to each transformation matrix to extract the local distortion information.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Remember that, because distortion is local, every location on the map will have its own transformation.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] It is the decomposition of the transformation, ${\mathcal {T}}$ , into a rotation in the source domain (i.e. the ellipsoid surface), $V^{T}$ , a scaling along the basis, $\Lambda$ , and a subsequent second rotation, U .
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] For understanding distortion, the first rotation is irrelevant, as it rotates the axes of the circle but has no bearing on the final orientation of the ellipse.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] The next operation, represented by the diagonal singular value matrix, scales the circle along its axes, deforming it to an ellipse.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Thus, the singular values represent the scale factors along axes of the ellipse.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] The first singular value provides the semi-major axis, a , and the second provides the semi-minor axis, b , which are the directional scaling factors of distortion.
[src:map-projections-viz/tissot-s-indicatrix] Scale distortion can be computed as the area of the ellipse, $ab$ , or equivalently by the determinant of ${\mathcal {T}}$ .
[src:map-projections-viz/winkel-tripel-projection] The **Winkel tripel projection** (**Winkel III**), a modified azimuthal map projection of the world, is one of three projections proposed by German cartographer Oswald Winkel in 1921.
[src:map-projections-viz/winkel-tripel-projection] The projection is the arithmetic mean of the equirectangular projection and the Aitoff projection: The name *tripel* (German for 'triple') refers to Winkel's goal of minimizing three kinds of distortion: area, direction, and distance.
[src:map-projections-viz/winkel-tripel-projection] A closed-form inverse mapping does not exist, and computing the inverse numerically requires the use of iterative methods.
[src:map-projections-viz/winkel-tripel-projection] Richard Gott III showed that the Winkel tripel fares better against several other projections analyzed against their measures of distortion, producing minimal distance, Tissot indicatrix ellipticity and area errors, and the least skew of any of the projections they studied.
[src:map-projections-viz/winkel-tripel-projection] By a different metric, Capek's "Q", the Winkel tripel ranked ninth among a hundred map projections of the world, behind the common Eckert IV projection and Robinson projections.
[src:map-projections-viz/winkel-tripel-projection] In 1998, the Winkel tripel projection replaced the Robinson projection as the standard projection for world maps made by the National Geographic Society.
[src:map-projections-viz/winkel-tripel-projection] Many educational institutes and textbooks soon followed National Geographic's example in adopting the projection, most of which still utilize it as of 2012.
